('chunk_d4aabf673cfd470edd','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Non-literary text — The Advertisement','**Why study it.** Advertisements are compact persuasive texts that reveal how creators shape identity and desire. They belong to Criterion A (analysing non-literary text) and feed the unit''s writing on persuasion.

**Analysis toolkit.**

| Element | Questions to ask |
|---------|------------------|
| **Purpose** | Is it selling a product, an idea, a lifestyle, a brand image? What action does it want? |
| **Target audience** | Who is it for (age, gender, interests)? How do you know? |
| **Visual elements** | Colour (warm/cool, brand colours), images, models, layout, focal point, use of space, typography/font. |
| **Language** | Slogan, tagline, imperatives ("Buy now"), puns, exaggeration. |
| **Persuasive techniques** | Ethos (credibility/celebrity endorsement), pathos (emotion), logos (facts/statistics), bandwagon ("everyone''s using it"), aspiration, humour, repetition. |

**Real-world use.** Being able to decode ads makes students critical consumers who resist manipulation and understand marketing — a media-literacy life skill.

**Analogy.** An advertisement is like a stage magician: it directs your attention to one shining thing (the focal image) so you don''t notice the choices being made to influence you.

**Command-term question.** *Analyse* how the visual elements and language of a chosen advertisement work together to persuade its target audience.','{"non":2,"literary":2,"text":2,"the":5,"advertisement":3,"why":1,"study":1,"advertisements":1,"are":1,"compact":1,"persuasive":2,"texts":1,"that":1,"reveal":1,"how":3,"creators":1,"shape":1,"identity":1,"and":4,"desire":1,"they":1,"belong":1,"criterion":1,"analysing":1,"feed":1,"unit":1,"writing":1,"persuasion":1,"analysis":1,"toolkit":1,"element":1,"questions":1,"ask":1,"purpose":1,"selling":1,"product":1,"idea":1,"lifestyle":1,"brand":2,"image":2,"what":1,"action":1,"does":1,"want":1,"target":2,"audience":2,"who":2,"for":1,"age":1,"gender":1,"interests":1,"you":3,"know":1,"visual":2,"elements":2,"colour":1,"warm":1,"cool":1,"colours":1,"images":1,"models":1,"layout":1,"focal":2,"point":1,"use":2,"space":1,"typography":1,"font":1,"language":2,"slogan":1,"tagline":1,"imperatives":1,"buy":1,"now":1,"puns":1,"exaggeration":1,"techniques":1,"ethos":1,"credibility":1,"celebrity":1,"endorsement":1,"pathos":1,"emotion":1,"logos":1,"facts":1,"statistics":1,"bandwagon":1,"everyone":1,"using":1,"aspiration":1,"humour":1,"repetition":1,"real":1,"world":1,"being":2,"able":1,"decode":1,"ads":1,"makes":1,"students":1,"critical":1,"consumers":1,"resist":1,"manipulation":1,"understand":1,"marketing":1,"media":1,"literacy":1,"life":1,"skill":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"stage":1,"magician":1,"directs":1,"your":1,"attention":1,"one":1,"shining":1,"thing":1,"don":1,"notice":1,"choices":1,"made":1,"influence":1,"command":1,"term":1,"question":1,"analyse":1,"chosen":1,"work":1,"together":1,"persuade":1,"its":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_7bea3459b920ec6a58','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Writing forms — Speech, Persuasive text, Persuasive blog','These three share the goal of **persuasion** but differ in medium and audience.','{"writing":1,"forms":1,"speech":1,"persuasive":2,"text":1,"blog":1,"these":1,"three":1,"share":1,"the":1,"goal":1,"persuasion":1,"but":1,"differ":1,"medium":1,"and":1,"audience":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_169da8230c72e81273','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Speech writing','- **Purpose:** to persuade, inspire or move a *listening* audience.
- **Audience:** present, live; cannot re-read, so ideas must be clear and repeated.
- **Structure/features:** strong hook/opening; clear thesis; 2-3 developed points; memorable close (call to action). Signposting ("First… Second… Finally").
- **Rhetorical devices:** *rhetorical questions*, *tricolon* (rule of three), *direct address* ("you"), *repetition/anaphora*, *emotive language*, *pauses*.
- **Checklist:** Hook? Clear stance? Rule of three? Rhetorical question? Call to action? Written for the ear (short sentences)?','{"speech":1,"writing":1,"purpose":1,"persuade":1,"inspire":1,"move":1,"listening":1,"audience":2,"present":1,"live":1,"cannot":1,"read":1,"ideas":1,"must":1,"clear":3,"and":1,"repeated":1,"structure":1,"features":1,"strong":1,"hook":2,"opening":1,"thesis":1,"developed":1,"points":1,"memorable":1,"close":1,"call":2,"action":2,"signposting":1,"first":1,"second":1,"finally":1,"rhetorical":3,"devices":1,"questions":1,"tricolon":1,"rule":2,"three":2,"direct":1,"address":1,"you":1,"repetition":1,"anaphora":1,"emotive":1,"language":1,"pauses":1,"checklist":1,"stance":1,"question":1,"written":1,"for":1,"the":1,"ear":1,"short":1,"sentences":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_c4031ccf1291be3bca','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Persuasive text','- **Purpose:** to convince a reader to accept a viewpoint or take action.
- **Structure:** introduction with a clear position → body paragraphs (point–evidence–explanation) → counter-argument + rebuttal → conclusion restating position.
- **Devices:** facts and statistics (logos), expert opinion (ethos), emotive appeals (pathos), modal verbs ("we must"), connectives of persuasion ("therefore," "as a result").','{"persuasive":1,"text":1,"purpose":1,"convince":1,"reader":1,"accept":1,"viewpoint":1,"take":1,"action":1,"structure":1,"introduction":1,"with":1,"clear":1,"position":2,"body":1,"paragraphs":1,"point":1,"evidence":1,"explanation":1,"counter":1,"argument":1,"rebuttal":1,"conclusion":1,"restating":1,"devices":1,"facts":1,"and":1,"statistics":1,"logos":1,"expert":1,"opinion":1,"ethos":1,"emotive":1,"appeals":1,"pathos":1,"modal":1,"verbs":1,"must":1,"connectives":1,"persuasion":1,"therefore":1,"result":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_2189951ac6a2af512a','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Persuasive blog','- **Purpose:** persuade an online audience; often personal and opinion-led.
- **Audience:** readers scrolling online — needs an engaging title, short paragraphs, subheadings.
- **Features:** informal but purposeful register; first-person voice; hyperlinks; a hook opening; direct reader address; a shareable, opinionated stance; call to action / invitation to comment.

**Mini worked model (blog opening).** *"Every morning, 800 million people wake up hungry — and I used to scroll right past that fact. Not anymore. Here''s why you should care too, and three things you can do before lunch today."* (Hook = statistic + personal turn; direct address; promise of a list.)

**Command-term question.** *Justify* which persuasive device is most effective for a live speech versus an online blog.','{"800":1,"persuasive":2,"blog":3,"purpose":1,"persuade":1,"online":3,"audience":2,"often":1,"personal":2,"and":3,"opinion":1,"led":1,"readers":1,"scrolling":1,"needs":1,"engaging":1,"title":1,"short":1,"paragraphs":1,"subheadings":1,"features":1,"informal":1,"but":1,"purposeful":1,"register":1,"first":1,"person":1,"voice":1,"hyperlinks":1,"hook":2,"opening":2,"direct":2,"reader":1,"address":2,"shareable":1,"opinionated":1,"stance":1,"call":1,"action":1,"invitation":1,"comment":1,"mini":1,"worked":1,"model":1,"every":1,"morning":1,"million":1,"people":1,"wake":1,"hungry":1,"used":1,"scroll":1,"right":1,"past":1,"that":1,"fact":1,"not":1,"anymore":1,"here":1,"why":1,"you":2,"should":1,"care":1,"too":1,"three":1,"things":1,"can":1,"before":1,"lunch":1,"today":1,"statistic":1,"turn":1,"promise":1,"list":1,"command":1,"term":1,"question":1,"justify":1,"which":1,"device":1,"most":1,"effective":1,"for":1,"live":1,"speech":1,"versus":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d295c8ffabb0b9e972','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Nouns','| Type | Definition | Example |
|------|-----------|---------|
| Common | general person/place/thing | *city, coach, shoe* |
| Proper | specific name (capitalised) | *Ghost, Brody, October* |
| Abstract | idea/feeling | *identity, courage, fear* |
| Collective | group | *team, crowd, family* |
| Countable/Uncountable | can/can''t be counted | *shoes / advice* |

- **Rule:** Proper nouns are always capitalised; abstract nouns name things you cannot touch.
- **Common error:** Capitalising common nouns for emphasis ("I love my School"). *Correction:* only proper nouns are capitalised → "I love my school."
- **Real-world use:** precise nouns make persuasive writing concrete.
- **Practice:** Identify the abstract noun — "His *bravery* on the track surprised everyone." (Answer: bravery.)','{"nouns":6,"type":1,"definition":1,"example":1,"common":3,"general":1,"person":1,"place":1,"thing":1,"city":1,"coach":1,"shoe":1,"proper":3,"specific":1,"name":2,"capitalised":3,"ghost":1,"brody":1,"october":1,"abstract":3,"idea":1,"feeling":1,"identity":1,"courage":1,"fear":1,"collective":1,"group":1,"team":1,"crowd":1,"family":1,"countable":1,"uncountable":1,"can":2,"counted":1,"shoes":1,"advice":1,"rule":1,"are":2,"always":1,"things":1,"you":1,"cannot":1,"touch":1,"error":1,"capitalising":1,"for":1,"emphasis":1,"love":2,"school":2,"correction":1,"only":1,"real":1,"world":1,"use":1,"precise":1,"make":1,"persuasive":1,"writing":1,"concrete":1,"practice":1,"identify":1,"the":2,"noun":1,"his":1,"bravery":2,"track":1,"surprised":1,"everyone":1,"answer":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_dfa321f11ec5e3f3cc','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Adjectives — degrees of comparison','| Degree | Use | Short adj. | Long adj. |
|--------|-----|-----------|-----------|
| Positive | describe one | fast | interesting |
| Comparative | compare two | faster | more interesting |
| Superlative | compare 3+ | fastest | most interesting |

- **Rule:** short (1-syllable) adjectives add *-er/-est*; longer adjectives use *more/most*. Irregulars: good–better–best; bad–worse–worst.
- **Common error:** "double comparatives" — "more faster," "most fastest." *Correction:* "faster," "fastest."
- **Analogy:** think of a podium — positive = one runner, comparative = two runners racing, superlative = the whole medal stand.
- **Practice:** Complete — "Ghost is the ___ (fast) runner on the team." (Answer: fastest.)','{"adjectives":3,"degrees":1,"comparison":1,"degree":1,"use":2,"short":2,"adj":2,"long":1,"positive":2,"describe":1,"one":2,"fast":2,"interesting":3,"comparative":2,"compare":2,"two":2,"faster":3,"more":3,"superlative":2,"fastest":4,"most":3,"rule":1,"syllable":1,"add":1,"est":1,"longer":1,"irregulars":1,"good":1,"better":1,"best":1,"bad":1,"worse":1,"worst":1,"common":1,"error":1,"double":1,"comparatives":1,"correction":1,"analogy":1,"think":1,"podium":1,"runner":2,"runners":1,"racing":1,"the":3,"whole":1,"medal":1,"stand":1,"practice":1,"complete":1,"ghost":1,"team":1,"answer":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_e5d9c310a4aacec2ac','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Articles','- **Rule:** *a/an* = indefinite (any one; *an* before a vowel *sound*); *the* = definite (a specific one). Use no article for general plurals/uncountables ("Shoes are expensive").
- **Common error:** "an university," "a hour." *Correction:* "a university" (yoo-sound), "an hour" (silent h) — go by sound, not spelling.
- **Practice:** "Ghost wanted ___ new pair of shoes; ___ shoes he chose were silver." (Answer: a; the.)','{"articles":1,"rule":1,"indefinite":1,"any":1,"one":2,"before":1,"vowel":1,"sound":3,"the":2,"definite":1,"specific":1,"use":1,"article":1,"for":1,"general":1,"plurals":1,"uncountables":1,"shoes":3,"are":1,"expensive":1,"common":1,"error":1,"university":2,"hour":2,"correction":1,"yoo":1,"silent":1,"not":1,"spelling":1,"practice":1,"ghost":1,"wanted":1,"new":1,"pair":1,"chose":1,"were":1,"silver":1,"answer":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_3922c74ee27eb2f787','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Pronouns','| Type | Examples |
|------|----------|
| Personal | I, you, he, she, it, we, they |
| Possessive | mine, yours, his, hers, ours, theirs |
| Reflexive | myself, yourself, themselves |
| Relative | who, whom, which, that |
| Demonstrative | this, that, these, those |

- **Rule:** a pronoun must agree with its antecedent (the noun it replaces) in number and gender.
- **Common error:** unclear reference — "Ghost told Lu that he was wrong" (who?). *Correction:* rewrite for clarity.
- **Practice:** Replace the repeated noun — "Coach praised Ghost because Ghost tried hard." (Answer: …because *he* tried hard.)','{"pronouns":1,"type":1,"examples":1,"personal":1,"you":1,"she":1,"they":1,"possessive":1,"mine":1,"yours":1,"his":1,"hers":1,"ours":1,"theirs":1,"reflexive":1,"myself":1,"yourself":1,"themselves":1,"relative":1,"who":2,"whom":1,"which":1,"that":3,"demonstrative":1,"this":1,"these":1,"those":1,"rule":1,"pronoun":1,"must":1,"agree":1,"with":1,"its":1,"antecedent":1,"the":2,"noun":2,"replaces":1,"number":1,"and":1,"gender":1,"common":1,"error":1,"unclear":1,"reference":1,"ghost":3,"told":1,"was":1,"wrong":1,"correction":1,"rewrite":1,"for":1,"clarity":1,"practice":1,"replace":1,"repeated":1,"coach":1,"praised":1,"because":2,"tried":2,"hard":2,"answer":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_31538c088485bf5fcd','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Adverbs','- **Rule:** adverbs modify verbs, adjectives or other adverbs, telling *how, when, where, how often, to what degree* (quickly, yesterday, here, always, very). Many end in *-ly*.
- **Common error:** using an adjective for an adverb — "He ran quick." *Correction:* "He ran quickly."
- **Analogy:** if adjectives are make-up for nouns, adverbs are make-up for verbs.
- **Practice:** Identify the adverb — "Ghost *impulsively* joined the race." (Answer: impulsively.)

---','{"adverbs":4,"rule":1,"modify":1,"verbs":2,"adjectives":2,"other":1,"telling":1,"how":2,"when":1,"where":1,"often":1,"what":1,"degree":1,"quickly":2,"yesterday":1,"here":1,"always":1,"very":1,"many":1,"end":1,"common":1,"error":1,"using":1,"adjective":1,"for":3,"adverb":2,"ran":2,"quick":1,"correction":1,"analogy":1,"are":2,"make":2,"nouns":1,"practice":1,"identify":1,"the":2,"ghost":1,"impulsively":2,"joined":1,"race":1,"answer":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_4d58389e279b5e9445','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Unit 2: How Do We Separate Fact from Fiction?','- **Key Concept:** Communication (with Connections)
- **Related Concepts:** Context, Genre, Point of view, Purpose
- **Global Context:** Fairness and Development
- **Statement of Inquiry:** Writers blend historical fact and imaginative fiction to communicate truths about fairness, injustice and the human experience.
- **Inquiry Questions:**
  - *Factual:* What is historical fiction? What features distinguish fact from fiction in a text?
  - *Conceptual:* How does context shape the way a story about injustice is told and received? How does genre guide a reader''s expectations?
  - *Debatable:* Can fiction tell a "truer" truth than a history textbook? Is it fair for writers to reimagine real historical events?','{"unit":1,"how":3,"separate":1,"fact":3,"from":2,"fiction":5,"key":1,"concept":1,"communication":1,"with":1,"connections":1,"related":1,"concepts":1,"context":3,"genre":2,"point":1,"view":1,"purpose":1,"global":1,"fairness":2,"and":4,"development":1,"statement":1,"inquiry":2,"writers":2,"blend":1,"historical":3,"imaginative":1,"communicate":1,"truths":1,"about":2,"injustice":2,"the":2,"human":1,"experience":1,"questions":1,"factual":1,"what":2,"features":1,"distinguish":1,"text":1,"conceptual":1,"does":2,"shape":1,"way":1,"story":1,"told":1,"received":1,"guide":1,"reader":1,"expectations":1,"debatable":1,"can":1,"tell":1,"truer":1,"truth":1,"than":1,"history":1,"textbook":1,"fair":1,"for":1,"reimagine":1,"real":1,"events":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_677ec16cd65c665e3d','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','"The Last Leaf" — William Sydney Porter (O. Henry)','**Summary.** In Greenwich Village, a young artist, Johnsy, falls gravely ill with pneumonia and becomes convinced she will die when the last leaf falls from the ivy vine outside her window. Her friend Sue cares for her. An old, failed artist downstairs, Behrman, who has long dreamed of painting a masterpiece, secretly paints a leaf on the wall during a freezing, stormy night so that the "last leaf" never falls — giving Johnsy the will to live. Johnsy recovers, but Behrman catches pneumonia from the exposure and dies. The painted leaf was his masterpiece.
**Author & context.** O. Henry (pen name of William Sydney Porter) was an American writer famous for warm, ironic stories with surprise "twist" endings. Early 20th-century New York.
**Themes.** Self-sacrifice; hope and the will to live; art as an act of love; the value of an unnoticed life.
**Devices.** Situational irony and the twist ending; symbolism (the leaf = hope/life); foreshadowing; characterisation of Behrman.
**Link to unit:** blends realistic setting with a fictional, meaningful event — communicating a truth about sacrifice and fairness (the "worthless" old man is the true hero).','{"the":14,"last":3,"leaf":6,"william":2,"sydney":2,"porter":2,"henry":2,"summary":1,"greenwich":1,"village":1,"young":1,"artist":2,"johnsy":3,"falls":3,"gravely":1,"ill":1,"with":3,"pneumonia":2,"and":5,"becomes":1,"convinced":1,"she":1,"will":3,"die":1,"when":1,"from":2,"ivy":1,"vine":1,"outside":1,"her":3,"window":1,"friend":1,"sue":1,"cares":1,"for":2,"old":2,"failed":1,"downstairs":1,"behrman":3,"who":1,"has":1,"long":1,"dreamed":1,"painting":1,"masterpiece":2,"secretly":1,"paints":1,"wall":1,"during":1,"freezing":1,"stormy":1,"night":1,"that":1,"never":1,"giving":1,"live":2,"recovers":1,"but":1,"catches":1,"exposure":1,"dies":1,"painted":1,"was":2,"his":1,"author":1,"context":1,"pen":1,"name":1,"american":1,"writer":1,"famous":1,"warm":1,"ironic":1,"stories":1,"surprise":1,"twist":2,"endings":1,"early":1,"20th":1,"century":1,"new":1,"york":1,"themes":1,"self":1,"sacrifice":2,"hope":2,"art":1,"act":1,"love":1,"value":1,"unnoticed":1,"life":2,"devices":1,"situational":1,"irony":1,"ending":1,"symbolism":1,"foreshadowing":1,"characterisation":1,"link":1,"unit":1,"blends":1,"realistic":1,"setting":1,"fictional":1,"meaningful":1,"event":1,"communicating":1,"truth":1,"about":1,"fairness":1,"worthless":1,"man":1,"true":1,"hero":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_6e1dceaff332276ca1','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','"The Drummer Boy of Shiloh" — Ray Bradbury','**Summary.** On the eve of the Battle of Shiloh (American Civil War, 1862), a frightened young drummer boy, Joby, lies awake, afraid he will be useless because he carries only a drum, not a weapon. The General walks the camp and speaks to him, explaining that the drummer is the "heart" of the army — his drumbeat sets the courage and pace of every soldier. Joby is reassured that he has a vital role.
**Author & context.** Ray Bradbury, celebrated American author; here writing historical fiction about a real Civil War battle.
**Themes.** Courage and fear; the importance of every individual; leadership and reassurance; coming of age.
**Devices.** Setting/atmosphere; the drum as a symbol of the army''s heartbeat; dialogue; imagery of the peach orchard soon to become a battlefield (dramatic irony — readers know Shiloh was horrific).
**Link to unit:** real historical battle + invented boy = fiction illuminating the human cost of war.','{"1862":1,"the":14,"drummer":3,"boy":3,"shiloh":3,"ray":2,"bradbury":2,"summary":1,"eve":1,"battle":3,"american":2,"civil":2,"war":3,"frightened":1,"young":1,"joby":2,"lies":1,"awake":1,"afraid":1,"will":1,"useless":1,"because":1,"carries":1,"only":1,"drum":2,"not":1,"weapon":1,"general":1,"walks":1,"camp":1,"and":4,"speaks":1,"him":1,"explaining":1,"that":2,"heart":1,"army":2,"his":1,"drumbeat":1,"sets":1,"courage":2,"pace":1,"every":2,"soldier":1,"reassured":1,"has":1,"vital":1,"role":1,"author":2,"context":1,"celebrated":1,"here":1,"writing":1,"historical":2,"fiction":2,"about":1,"real":2,"themes":1,"fear":1,"importance":1,"individual":1,"leadership":1,"reassurance":1,"coming":1,"age":1,"devices":1,"setting":1,"atmosphere":1,"symbol":1,"heartbeat":1,"dialogue":1,"imagery":1,"peach":1,"orchard":1,"soon":1,"become":1,"battlefield":1,"dramatic":1,"irony":1,"readers":1,"know":1,"was":1,"horrific":1,"link":1,"unit":1,"invented":1,"illuminating":1,"human":1,"cost":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_3625edce4fc5448919','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','"The Bracelet" — Yoshiko Uchida','**Summary.** During World War II, a Japanese-American girl, Ruri, and her family are forced from their California home into an internment camp. Her best friend Laurie gives her a gold bracelet as a keepsake. At the bleak camp, Ruri loses the bracelet — and realises she does not need an object to remember her friend; the memory lives inside her.
**Author & context.** Yoshiko Uchida drew on her own family''s internment. Set 1942, based on the real, unjust internment of Japanese Americans.
**Themes.** Injustice and prejudice; memory and friendship; loss of home and dignity; resilience.
**Devices.** First-person narration; symbolism (the bracelet = friendship/memory); setting as instrument of injustice; understated tone.
**Link to unit:** directly connects fiction to a factual injustice — the core of the *Fairness and Development* context.','{"1942":1,"the":8,"bracelet":4,"yoshiko":2,"uchida":2,"summary":1,"during":1,"world":1,"war":1,"japanese":2,"american":1,"girl":1,"ruri":2,"and":6,"her":6,"family":2,"are":1,"forced":1,"from":1,"their":1,"california":1,"home":2,"into":1,"internment":3,"camp":2,"best":1,"friend":2,"laurie":1,"gives":1,"gold":1,"keepsake":1,"bleak":1,"loses":1,"realises":1,"she":1,"does":1,"not":1,"need":1,"object":1,"remember":1,"memory":3,"lives":1,"inside":1,"author":1,"context":2,"drew":1,"own":1,"set":1,"based":1,"real":1,"unjust":1,"americans":1,"themes":1,"injustice":3,"prejudice":1,"friendship":2,"loss":1,"dignity":1,"resilience":1,"devices":1,"first":1,"person":1,"narration":1,"symbolism":1,"setting":1,"instrument":1,"understated":1,"tone":1,"link":1,"unit":1,"directly":1,"connects":1,"fiction":1,"factual":1,"core":1,"fairness":1,"development":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_191ef116e36887ea19','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','"Boxes" — Sampurna Chattarji','**Summary.** A contemporary story exploring how people and identities get put into "boxes" — categories, labels and confinements, literal and metaphorical. It invites students to question rigid categorisation and the way society sorts people.
**Author & context.** Sampurna Chattarji is an Indian poet, writer and translator known for inventive, layered work.
**Themes.** Labels and categorisation; identity; the limits imposed by society; perspective.
**Devices.** Extended metaphor of the "box"; symbolism; shifting perspective.
**Link to unit:** questions how we categorise "fact" about people and how fair such labelling is.

**Command-term questions (short stories).**
- *Compare* how "The Bracelet" and "The Last Leaf" use a single object as a symbol.
- *Analyse* how Bradbury builds atmosphere before the battle.
- *Evaluate* which story most powerfully communicates injustice. Justify.','{"boxes":2,"sampurna":2,"chattarji":2,"summary":1,"contemporary":1,"story":2,"exploring":1,"how":5,"people":3,"and":8,"identities":1,"get":1,"put":1,"into":1,"categories":1,"labels":2,"confinements":1,"literal":1,"metaphorical":1,"invites":1,"students":1,"question":1,"rigid":1,"categorisation":2,"the":6,"way":1,"society":2,"sorts":1,"author":1,"context":1,"indian":1,"poet":1,"writer":1,"translator":1,"known":1,"for":1,"inventive":1,"layered":1,"work":1,"themes":1,"identity":1,"limits":1,"imposed":1,"perspective":2,"devices":1,"extended":1,"metaphor":1,"box":1,"symbolism":1,"shifting":1,"link":1,"unit":1,"questions":2,"categorise":1,"fact":1,"about":1,"fair":1,"such":1,"labelling":1,"command":1,"term":1,"short":1,"stories":1,"compare":1,"bracelet":1,"last":1,"leaf":1,"use":1,"single":1,"object":1,"symbol":1,"analyse":1,"bradbury":1,"builds":1,"atmosphere":1,"before":1,"battle":1,"evaluate":1,"which":1,"most":1,"powerfully":1,"communicates":1,"injustice":1,"justify":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_ccdcecebf1b728ebcd','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','"These Are the Times We Live In" — Imtiaz Dharker','- **Poet:** Imtiaz Dharker, Pakistan-born British poet exploring identity, borders and belonging.
- **Subject:** the alienation and suspicion faced by migrants/travellers, especially the experience of being scrutinised at borders and treated as an outsider.
- **Form/structure:** free verse; fragmented, unsettling movement mirroring dislocation.
- **Devices:** second-person address, repetition, imagery of documents/checkpoints, irony.
- **Theme:** identity under suspicion; belonging and displacement in the modern world.
- **Teaching angle:** connect to real news about migration and borders — how poetry captures "these times."','{"these":2,"are":1,"the":4,"times":2,"live":1,"imtiaz":2,"dharker":2,"poet":2,"pakistan":1,"born":1,"british":1,"exploring":1,"identity":2,"borders":3,"and":5,"belonging":2,"subject":1,"alienation":1,"suspicion":2,"faced":1,"migrants":1,"travellers":1,"especially":1,"experience":1,"being":1,"scrutinised":1,"treated":1,"outsider":1,"form":1,"structure":1,"free":1,"verse":1,"fragmented":1,"unsettling":1,"movement":1,"mirroring":1,"dislocation":1,"devices":1,"second":1,"person":1,"address":1,"repetition":1,"imagery":1,"documents":1,"checkpoints":1,"irony":1,"theme":1,"under":1,"displacement":1,"modern":1,"world":1,"teaching":1,"angle":1,"connect":1,"real":1,"news":1,"about":1,"migration":1,"how":1,"poetry":1,"captures":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_314e1319e6c7fab9a1','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','"The Migrants"','- **Subject:** the plight, journey and hopes of migrants forced to leave home.
- **Form/structure:** typically free verse; collective voice.
- **Devices:** imagery of journey and loss, symbolism of home, contrast between old and new lands.
- **Theme:** displacement, survival, dignity, and fairness toward the displaced.
- **Teaching angle:** pair with "These Are the Times We Live In" to compare two treatments of migration; discuss *Fairness and Development*.','{"the":4,"migrants":2,"subject":1,"plight":1,"journey":2,"and":5,"hopes":1,"forced":1,"leave":1,"home":2,"form":1,"structure":1,"typically":1,"free":1,"verse":1,"collective":1,"voice":1,"devices":1,"imagery":1,"loss":1,"symbolism":1,"contrast":1,"between":1,"old":1,"new":1,"lands":1,"theme":1,"displacement":1,"survival":1,"dignity":1,"fairness":2,"toward":1,"displaced":1,"teaching":1,"angle":1,"pair":1,"with":1,"these":1,"are":1,"times":1,"live":1,"compare":1,"two":1,"treatments":1,"migration":1,"discuss":1,"development":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_1bc190dfc0228dc7d2','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','"We Wear the Mask" — Paul Laurence Dunbar','- **Poet:** Paul Laurence Dunbar (1872-1906), one of the first African-American poets to gain national prominence; son of formerly enslaved parents.
- **Subject:** how oppressed people — specifically African Americans after slavery — hide their real pain and suffering behind a smiling, cheerful "mask" to survive in a prejudiced society.
- **Form/structure:** a *rondeau* — 15 lines, tight rhyme scheme, with the refrain "We wear the mask" repeated. The controlled form mirrors controlled, hidden emotion.
- **Devices:** the central metaphor/symbol of the *mask*; refrain; contrast between outward smile and inward "torn and bleeding hearts"; the collective "we."
- **Theme:** concealment of suffering; the psychological cost of oppression; dignity under injustice.
- **Teaching angle:** the gap between appearance (fiction of the smile) and reality (fact of the pain) — a perfect fit for "fact vs fiction" and *Fairness*.

**Command-term question (poetry).** *Compare* how Dunbar and Dharker use a controlling image (mask / border) to expose injustice.','{"1872":1,"1906":1,"wear":2,"the":12,"mask":5,"paul":2,"laurence":2,"dunbar":3,"poet":1,"one":1,"first":1,"african":2,"american":1,"poets":1,"gain":1,"national":1,"prominence":1,"son":1,"formerly":1,"enslaved":1,"parents":1,"subject":1,"how":2,"oppressed":1,"people":1,"specifically":1,"americans":1,"after":1,"slavery":1,"hide":1,"their":1,"real":1,"pain":2,"and":6,"suffering":2,"behind":1,"smiling":1,"cheerful":1,"survive":1,"prejudiced":1,"society":1,"form":2,"structure":1,"rondeau":1,"lines":1,"tight":1,"rhyme":1,"scheme":1,"with":1,"refrain":2,"repeated":1,"controlled":2,"mirrors":1,"hidden":1,"emotion":1,"devices":1,"central":1,"metaphor":1,"symbol":1,"contrast":1,"between":2,"outward":1,"smile":2,"inward":1,"torn":1,"bleeding":1,"hearts":1,"collective":1,"theme":1,"concealment":1,"psychological":1,"cost":1,"oppression":1,"dignity":1,"under":1,"injustice":2,"teaching":1,"angle":1,"gap":1,"appearance":1,"fiction":2,"reality":1,"fact":2,"perfect":1,"fit":1,"for":1,"fairness":1,"command":1,"term":1,"question":1,"poetry":1,"compare":1,"dharker":1,"use":1,"controlling":1,"image":1,"border":1,"expose":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_43d7556f3c7d369070','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Non-literary / Writing — Narrative Writing and Alternate Ending','- **Purpose:** to tell an engaging, coherent story (or to reimagine an existing one).
- **Audience:** readers seeking to be entertained and moved.
- **Structure/features:** orientation (setting/characters) → rising action → climax → falling action → resolution (Freytag''s pyramid). Point of view, consistent tense, showing not telling.
- **Devices:** vivid imagery, dialogue, sensory detail, pacing, foreshadowing.
- **Alternate ending:** rewrite a studied text''s conclusion while staying true to established characters, setting and voice. Ask: what if Behrman had *not* painted the leaf? What if Ruri had *kept* the bracelet?
- **Checklist:** Consistent point of view? Established characters stay believable? Clear turning point? Sensory detail? Satisfying (even if unhappy) resolution?

**Command-term question.** *Justify* how your alternate ending remains consistent with the original characters.','{"non":1,"literary":1,"writing":2,"narrative":1,"and":3,"alternate":3,"ending":3,"purpose":1,"tell":1,"engaging":1,"coherent":1,"story":1,"reimagine":1,"existing":1,"one":1,"audience":1,"readers":1,"seeking":1,"entertained":1,"moved":1,"structure":1,"features":1,"orientation":1,"setting":2,"characters":4,"rising":1,"action":2,"climax":1,"falling":1,"resolution":2,"freytag":1,"pyramid":1,"point":3,"view":2,"consistent":3,"tense":1,"showing":1,"not":2,"telling":1,"devices":1,"vivid":1,"imagery":1,"dialogue":1,"sensory":2,"detail":2,"pacing":1,"foreshadowing":1,"rewrite":1,"studied":1,"text":1,"conclusion":1,"while":1,"staying":1,"true":1,"established":2,"voice":1,"ask":1,"what":2,"behrman":1,"had":2,"painted":1,"the":3,"leaf":1,"ruri":1,"kept":1,"bracelet":1,"checklist":1,"stay":1,"believable":1,"clear":1,"turning":1,"satisfying":1,"even":1,"unhappy":1,"command":1,"term":1,"question":1,"justify":1,"how":1,"your":1,"remains":1,"with":1,"original":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_51eb6e1907ba5e4da8','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Prepositions','- **Rule:** prepositions show relationships of place, time or direction between a noun/pronoun and other words (*in, on, at, under, before, between, across*).
- **Common error:** "different than" vs "different from"; ending confusion. Also *in/on/at* time rules: *at* 5 o''clock, *on* Monday, *in* July.
- **Practice:** "The ivy grew ___ the wall ___ November." (Answer: on; in.)','{"prepositions":2,"rule":1,"show":1,"relationships":1,"place":1,"time":2,"direction":1,"between":2,"noun":1,"pronoun":1,"and":1,"other":1,"words":1,"under":1,"before":1,"across":1,"common":1,"error":1,"different":2,"than":1,"from":1,"ending":1,"confusion":1,"also":1,"rules":1,"clock":1,"monday":1,"july":1,"practice":1,"the":2,"ivy":1,"grew":1,"wall":1,"november":1,"answer":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_6f9f89d876a637f889','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Conjunctions','| Type | Examples | Job |
|------|----------|-----|
| Coordinating (FANBOYS) | for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so | join equal parts |
| Subordinating | because, although, while, since, if | join a dependent clause |
| Correlative | either…or, neither…nor, not only…but also | work in pairs |

- **Common error:** comma splice — joining two full sentences with only a comma. *Correction:* use a coordinating conjunction or a semicolon: "Johnsy was ill, *but* Behrman helped."
- **Practice:** Join with a subordinating conjunction — "Ruri lost the bracelet. She still remembered Laurie." (e.g., *Although* Ruri lost the bracelet, she still remembered Laurie.)','{"conjunctions":1,"type":1,"examples":1,"job":1,"coordinating":2,"fanboys":1,"for":1,"and":1,"nor":2,"but":3,"yet":1,"join":3,"equal":1,"parts":1,"subordinating":2,"because":1,"although":2,"while":1,"since":1,"dependent":1,"clause":1,"correlative":1,"either":1,"neither":1,"not":1,"only":2,"also":1,"work":1,"pairs":1,"common":1,"error":1,"comma":2,"splice":1,"joining":1,"two":1,"full":1,"sentences":1,"with":2,"correction":1,"use":1,"conjunction":2,"semicolon":1,"johnsy":1,"was":1,"ill":1,"behrman":1,"helped":1,"practice":1,"ruri":2,"lost":2,"the":2,"bracelet":2,"she":2,"still":2,"remembered":2,"laurie":2}'::jsonb),
('chunk_285552fbc3f144d940','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Tenses — Perfect and Continuous','| Tense | Form | Example | Use |
|-------|------|---------|-----|
| Present perfect | have/has + past participle | She *has painted* a leaf. | past action, present relevance |
| Past perfect | had + past participle | He *had dreamed* of a masterpiece. | earlier of two past actions |
| Present continuous | am/is/are + -ing | The snow *is falling*. | action happening now |
| Past continuous | was/were + -ing | They *were waiting* for the leaf to fall. | ongoing past action |
| Present perfect continuous | have/has been + -ing | It *has been snowing* all night. | ongoing up to now |

- **Common error:** mixing tenses within one narrative ("She walks to the window and saw the leaf"). *Correction:* keep tense consistent — "She walked… and saw…"
- **Practice:** Choose — "By the time Johnsy recovered, Behrman ___ (die)." (Answer: had died — past perfect.)','{"tenses":2,"perfect":5,"and":3,"continuous":4,"tense":2,"form":1,"example":1,"use":1,"present":4,"have":2,"has":4,"past":8,"participle":2,"she":3,"painted":1,"leaf":3,"action":3,"relevance":1,"had":3,"dreamed":1,"masterpiece":1,"earlier":1,"two":1,"actions":1,"are":1,"ing":3,"the":5,"snow":1,"falling":1,"happening":1,"now":2,"was":1,"were":2,"they":1,"waiting":1,"for":1,"fall":1,"ongoing":2,"been":2,"snowing":1,"all":1,"night":1,"common":1,"error":1,"mixing":1,"within":1,"one":1,"narrative":1,"walks":1,"window":1,"saw":2,"correction":1,"keep":1,"consistent":1,"walked":1,"practice":1,"choose":1,"time":1,"johnsy":1,"recovered":1,"behrman":1,"die":1,"answer":1,"died":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_4ac49d616537e53ebb','file_9635f055da2d10cf4a','language-and-literature.md','Subject-verb agreement','- **Rule:** the verb agrees with the subject in number. Singular subject → singular verb.
- **Common errors:** (1) intervening phrases — "The box of letters *were* lost" → *was* (subject is *box*). (2) Collective nouns usually take singular — "The team *is* ready." (3) *Either/neither… nor* → verb agrees with the nearer subject.
- **Practice:** "Each of the migrants ___ (carry) a story." (Answer: carries.)

